@robfuscator is actually right, my keyboard has been charged recently so no warnings till yesterday. I had a look at the recent upower (0.99.9) code and the battery warning level are hardcoded. So the adjustments in the config file were of no use after all. I recompiled upower with a temporary workaround, just change the values in up-daemon.c:652
``` C
	/* Keyboard and mice usually have a coarser
	 * battery level, so this avoids falling directly
	 * into critical (or off) before any warnings */
	if (kind == UP_DEVICE_KIND_MOUSE ||
	    kind == UP_DEVICE_KIND_KEYBOARD) {
		if (percentage <= 5.0f)
			return UP_DEVICE_LEVEL_CRITICAL;
		else if (percentage <= 10.0f)
			return  UP_DEVICE_LEVEL_LOW;
		else
			return UP_DEVICE_LEVEL_NONE;
	} else if (kind == UP_DEVICE_KIND_UPS) {
		default_level = UP_DEVICE_LEVEL_DISCHARGING;
	}
```

Hi,
I also took a quick look - I can try to help you get started:-

1. Try to reproduce the issue without changing your computers clock back to January

a) Modify *src/gcal-application.c* around line 310 set the initial_date to a day in January

```
//*self->initial_date = icaltime_current_time_with_zone (tz);
*self->initial_date = icaltime_from_day_of_year(10, 2018);
```

b) Modify *src/gcal-date-chooser.c* around line 560 to also set a January day

```
//self->date = g_date_time_new_now_local ();
self->date = g_date_time_new_local (2018, 1, 10, 0, 0, 0);
```

Note: The above two changes are for DEBUG only and are not part of the fix


2. FIX to prevent random NULL assertion with GDateTime object:- (i.e. don't let year be zero)

a) Modify *data/ui/date-chooser.ui* around lines 28-31 for the year_chooser which uses incorrect default values

- change *min-value* from 0 to 1
- change *max-value* from 120000 to 9999
- change *value* from 0 to 1

Note: I think this SHOULD be included in the patched (maybe a separate issue though)


At this point you should be able to run the application and reproduce the issue

3. Possible fix:-
a) Modify *src/gcal-date-chooser.c* around line 642 to FORCE the faulty widget to update its display

```
calendar_compute_days (self);
g_date_time_get_ymd (self->date, &year, &month, NULL);

// FORCE an update in the following code by temporarily setting the month to February
if (month == 1)
  gcal_multi_choice_set_value (GCAL_MULTI_CHOICE (self->month_choice), month);

gcal_multi_choice_set_value (GCAL_MULTI_CHOICE (self->year_choice), year);
gcal_multi_choice_set_value (GCAL_MULTI_CHOICE (self->month_choice), month - 1);
```

Note The last line above will change it to the correct month - its a bit of a hack but seems to work.

Cheers,
Paul

@rockon999 I think it'll be pretty bad to use an `npm` scope, because it has a meaning in npm, so it's a breaking interop proposal out of the box.

The `gi://` or `gir://` seems to be way more appropriate, specially for the URL standard behavior any JS module has these days, and the ability to specify the version via `?v=X`.

Historically all things are imported from `imports.gi` though, so I wonder why not sticking with `gi://`, but I personally woudn't mind `gir://` neither, since after all these all come from `gir` details.
